 To align a row of divs to the right using flex in CSS, you can use the justify-content property with the value "flex-end". Here's an example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <style>
      .container {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: flex-end;
      }
      .box {
        width: 100px;
        height: 100px;
        background-color: #ddd;
        margin: 5px;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="box"></div>
      <div class="box"></div>
      <div class="box"></div>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
```

In this example, the `.container` div has its display property set to flex and its justify-content property set to "flex-end". This will align all of its child elements (in this case, the `.box` divs) to the right side of the container. The `.box` divs are styled with a width, height, background color, and margin for demonstration purposes.
